{"id": 38, "ts": 1778868196.5041718, "event": "public_discussion_message", "round": 1, "agent": "agent_3", "message": "From the data we each hold, the picture of the four candidates can be summarised as follows:\n**Candidate\u202fA** \u2013 Strong analytical abilities (anticipates danger, sees complex connections, excellent spatial vision, very good leadership). However, there is no information about his calmness under pressure or his ability to work with a crew, and he is described as unfriendly and has unhealthy eating habits.\n**Candidate\u202fB** \u2013 Explicitly 100\u202f% reliable and keeps calm in a crisis \u2013 the two most critical attributes for long\u2011haul safety. He also has solid technical skills (weather assessment, computer proficiency). The only noted drawback is interpersonal: he can adopt the wrong tone and is regarded as pretentious, but no evidence suggests a failure to cooperate with the crew.\n**Candidate\u202fC** \u2013 Demonstrates good stress handling (\u201chandles stress very well\u201d) and can make correct decisions quickly, with excellent attention skills and a strong concern for others. Yet he has difficulty communicating ideas, is seen as egocentric, and is not eager to pursue further education \u2013 all of which could hinder crew coordination and long\u2011term development.\n**Candidate\u202fD** \u2013 Shows strong problem\u2011solving, concentration, and a serious sense of responsibility, and \u201cresponds to unexpected events adequately,\u201d indicating reasonable composure. Nevertheless, he is described as moody, a loner, arrogant, with a hot temper and weak leadership, and we have no concrete evidence of effective teamwork or communication.\nBalancing the selection criteria\u2014reliability, calmness under pressure, technical competence, sound decision\u2011making, and crew cooperation\u2014**Candidate\u202fB** aligns best with the core requirements of a long\u2011distance pilot. His proven reliability and crisis calmness